  "prompt": "I have anxiety and depression; was diagnosed less than a year ago. I recently went through a break up... How can I get myself to do things I like?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're going through this. Dealing with anxiety, depression, and a recent breakup can feel overwhelming. Here are some strategies that might help you reconnect with activities you enjoy:\n\n1. **Start Small**: Begin with tiny, manageable tasks. Even small accomplishments can boost your mood and motivation. For example, if you enjoy reading, start with reading a few pages each day.\n\n2. **Establish a Routine**: Creating a daily schedule can provide structure and a sense of normalcy. Include specific times for activities you like, as well as self-care practices.\n\n3. **Set Realistic Goals**: Break down activities into achievable steps. Instead of committing to a full workout, perhaps just aim to stretch or take a short walk.\n\n4. **Connect with Others**: Reach out to friends or family members who uplift you. Social support can make engaging in activities feel less daunting.\n\n5. **Practice Self-Compassion**: Be kind to yourself. It's okay to have days when you don't feel up to doing much. Acknowledge your feelings without judgment.\n\n6. **Engage in Physical Activity**: Exercise can help reduce symptoms of anxiety and depression. Activities like walking, yoga, or dancing can be both enjoyable and beneficial.\n\n7. **Explore New Interests**: Trying something new can reignite your passion and provide a fresh perspective. This could be a hobby you've always wanted to try or a class you've been curious about.\n\n8. **Mindfulness and Relaxation Techniques**: Practices such as meditation, deep breathing, or journaling can help manage stress and improve your emotional well-being.\n\n9. **Limit Stressors**: Identify and minimize sources of stress where possible. This might include setting boundaries, reducing screen time, or creating a calming environment.\n\n10. **Seek Professional Support**: Therapists or counselors can provide personalized strategies and support to help you navigate your feelings and regain interest in activities you enjoy.\n\nRemember, it's okay to seek help and take things at your own pace. You're not alone, and support is available to help you through this challenging time.",
